~tuningMap = Array.newClear(128);
(0..127).do { |j| ~tuningMap[j] = Array.fill(128, { |i| i }) };

// This creates an array of 128 possible tuning maps. Each map has 128 slots with MIDIfloat pitch information corresponding to SINGLE-channel MIDI notes. Default setting in this app is a MULTI-channel implementation (i.e., to play from a Lumatone mapping) where each channel automatically tranposes tuning map data by a number of "equaves" up or down, based on the channel's offset from a central (untransposed) channel. To optimise polyphonic treatment of unisons, the 16 MIDI channels are treated as TWO cycles of 8 equaves (channel 1 and channel 9 share the same transposition, etc.). The default central channel is 4, so that MIDI note 60 in understood to be C4 in the standard International pitch nomenclature. The actual frequency values triggered depend, of course, on the tuning map. By activating MTS (MIDI tuning standard sysex and sending single-note tuning change messages, for example from the hexatone app at hexatone.plainsound.org, it it possible to load different tuning maps from scala files of one's choice into any of the tuning map "slots". The tuning map may be globally transposed by a ratio or cents value (see VARIABLES below).

//Post << ~tuningMap[0];

